    <section class="tool-explainer">
      <h2>How to use the Percentage Calculator</h2>
      <p>Choose the type of percentage problem from the three tabs above, fill in the known values, and the answer appears immediately. Switch between modes at any time.</p>

      <h2>How percentage calculations work</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>X% of Y:</strong> Result = (X &divide; 100) &times; Y. Example: 20% of 150 = 30.<br>
        <strong>X is what % of Y:</strong> Result = (X &divide; Y) &times; 100. Example: 30 is what % of 150 = 20%.<br>
        <strong>Percentage change:</strong> Result = ((New &minus; Old) &divide; Old) &times; 100. A positive result is an increase; negative is a decrease.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I find 15% of a number?</h3>
          <p>Multiply the number by 0.15. For example, 15% of 200 = 200 &times; 0.15 = 30. You can also find 10% first (move the decimal one place left), then add half of that to get 15%. Example: 10% of 200 = 20, half = 10, so 15% = 30.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is the difference between percentage and percentage points?</h3>
          <p>A percentage is a fraction of 100 (e.g., an interest rate of 5%). A percentage point is an arithmetic difference between two percentages. If rates rise from 5% to 7%, that is a 2 percentage-point increase, but a 40% relative increase.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I calculate a percentage increase?</h3>
          <p>Subtract the original value from the new value, divide the result by the original value, then multiply by 100. Example: price rose from $40 to $50 → ((50 − 40) ÷ 40) × 100 = 25% increase.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I reverse a percentage — for example, find the original price before a 20% discount?</h3>
          <p>Divide the discounted price by (1 − discount rate). Example: sale price is $80 after a 20% discount → original price = $80 ÷ 0.80 = $100. Do not simply add 20% back — that gives the wrong answer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What does a negative percentage change mean?</h3>
          <p>A negative percentage change means the value decreased. For example, going from 100 to 75 is a −25% change, meaning a 25% decrease. The sign tells you the direction; the number tells you the magnitude.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

